# Remove stopwords and perform lemmatization

lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))

# Function to remove stopwords and perform lemmatization

def clean_tokens(tokens):
    return [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word.lower()) for word in tokens if word.isalpha() and word.lower() not in stop_words]

corona_nlp_train['CleanedTweet'] = corona_nlp_train['TokenizedTweet'].progress_apply(clean_tokens)
corona_nlp_test['CleanedTweet'] = corona_nlp_test['TokenizedTweet'].progress_apply(clean_tokens)

# Drop the 'TokenizedTweet' column as it's no longer needed

corona_nlp_train.drop(columns=['TokenizedTweet'], inplace=True)
corona_nlp_test.drop(columns=['TokenizedTweet'], inplace=True)

# Ensure both dataframes have the same columns

columns_to_keep = ['UserName', 'ScreenName', 'Location', 'TweetAt', 'OriginalTweet', 'Sentiment', 'CleanedTweet']
corona_nlp_train = corona_nlp_train[columns_to_keep]
corona_nlp_test = corona_nlp_test[columns_to_keep]

# Display the head of both dataframes to confirm

corona_nlp_train.head(), corona_nlp_test.head()

def clean_tokens(tokens):
    return [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word.lower()) for word in tokens if word.isalpha() and word.lower() not in stop_words]

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Visualize the distribution of sentiment categories
sentiment_counts = corona_nlp_train['Sentiment'].value_counts()

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.bar(sentiment_counts.index, sentiment_counts.values, color='skyblue')
plt.title('Distribution of Sentiment Categories')
plt.xlabel('Sentiment Category')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.show()

The bar chart above displays the distribution of sentiment categories in the training dataset. Each sentiment category is represented on the x-axis, while the count of tweets associated with each sentiment is shown on the y-axis. This visualization provides a clear representation of the balance or imbalance between different sentiment classes, allowing us to observe which sentiments are more prevalent and which are less common in the dataset.

In[25]:
from wordcloud import WordCloud
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Generate word clouds for each sentiment category
sentiment_categories = corona_nlp_train['Sentiment'].unique()

# Set up subplots for word clouds
num_categories = len(sentiment_categories)
rows = int(num_categories / 2) + (num_categories % 2)
cols = 2

fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, cols, figsize=(15, 8))

for i, category in enumerate(sentiment_categories):
    text = ' '.join(corona_nlp_train[corona_nlp_train['Sentiment'] == category]['CleanedTweet'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join(x)).values)
    wordcloud = WordCloud(width=400, height=200, background_color='white').generate(text)
    ax = axes[int(i / 2), i % 2] if num_categories > 1 else axes
    ax.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
    ax.set_title('Word Cloud for Sentiment Category: ' + category)
    ax.axis('off')

# Remove empty subplots if needed
if num_categories % 2 != 0:
    fig.delaxes(axes[rows - 1, 1])

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The word clouds above represent the most frequent words found in tweets for each sentiment category within the training dataset. Each word cloud corresponds to a different sentiment, providing a visual representation of the words that are most characteristic of each sentiment.

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd

# Convert the timestamp to datetime
corona_nlp_train['TweetAt'] = pd.to_datetime(corona_nlp_train['TweetAt'])

# Group by date and sentiment to get the count of tweets for each sentiment on each date
sentiment_trends = corona_nlp_train.groupby([corona_nlp_train['TweetAt'].dt.date, 'Sentiment']).size().unstack()

# Plot the sentiment trends over time
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.lineplot(data=sentiment_trends, markers=True)
plt.title('Sentiment Trends Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Number of Tweets')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

From this chart it is seen that people tried to be more hopeful and positive when the covid era peaked in the month of march 2020. The line of being extremely negative is always low which says that twitter consists of people (or alleged bots) who try to have a positive outlook on life.

It is also seen to be negative during the peak time of March 2020, but not extremely negative. Which gives us a reality check at the same time. This data is interesting to see in this way.

Next, I will be performing Logistic Regression on the data - to build a model that can predict the sentiment of tweets based on their content. The logistic regression model uses the cleaned tweet data to learn the relationship between the words in the tweets and the sentiment labels. By training this model, I aim to accurately classify tweets into different sentiment categories, which can provide valuable insights into public sentiment during the COVID-19 pandemic.

In[28]:
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report


# Initialize the TfidfVectorizer
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(max_features=1000)

# Fit and transform the training data
X_train = vectorizer.fit_transform(train_tweets)

# Transform the test data
X_test = vectorizer.transform(test_tweets)

# Define the target variable
y_train = corona_nlp_train['Sentiment']
y_test = corona_nlp_test['Sentiment']

# Initialize the Logistic Regression model
model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)

# Fit the model on the training data
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predict the sentiment on the test data
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Calculate the accuracy
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)

# Generate the classification report
report = classification_report(y_test, y_pred)

# Displaying the results
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}\n")
print("Classification Report:")
print(report)
